e","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1262–1364":"omkring 1262–1364","1256–1331":"1256–1331","1286–1364":"1286–1364","1287–Male":"1287–Afdød","1289–Female":"1289–Afdød","1295–1347":"1295–1347","1262–1364":"1262–1364","about 1280":"omkring 1280","1286":"1286","1295":"1295","1262":"1262","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1347":"1347","1289":"1289","1256":"1256","about 1347":"omkring 1347","1331":"1331","1364":"1364","1287":"1287","about 1289":"omkring 1289","about 1286":"omkring 1286","about 1287":"omkring 1287","about 1262":"omkring 1262","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1262–1364":"circa 1262–1364","1256–1331":"1256–1331","1286–1364":"1286–1364","1287–Male":"1287–Overleden","1289–Female":"1289–Overleden","1295–1347":"1295–1347","1262–1364":"1262–1364","about 1280":"circa 1280","1286":"1286","1295":"1295","1262":"1262","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1347":"1347","1289":"1289","1256":"1256","about 1347":"circa 1347","1331":"1331","1364":"1364","1287":"1287","about 1289":"circa 1289","about 1286":"circa 1286","about 1287":"circa 1287","about 1262":"circa 1262","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1262–1364":"about 1262–1364","1256–1331":"1256–1331","1286–1364":"1286–1364","1287–Male":"1287–Deceased","1289–Female":"1289–Deceased","1295–1347":"1295–1347","1262–1364":"1262–1364","about 1280":"about 1280","1286":"1286","1295":"1295","1262":"1262","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1347":"1347","1289":"1289","1256":"1256","about 1347":"about 1347","1331":"1331","1364":"1364","1287":"1287","about 1289":"about 1289","about 1286":"about 1286","about 1287":"about 1287","about 1262":"about 1262","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cook","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cookson","meanings":["English (Lancashire): from Middle English <i>cok</i> ‘cook’ or the surname <i>Cook</i> + <i>son</i>, denoting either ‘son of (the) cook’ or ‘son of (a man called) Cook’. See   Cook  ."]},{"name":"Cocke","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>cok</i> (Old English and Old French <i>coc</i>) ‘rooster’.","patronymic from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cok</i>, of uncertain origin but perhaps derived from the word in 1 above."]},{"name":"Coke","meanings":["English: variant of   Cook   or   Cocke  .","Americanized form of German   Koke   or   Koch  ."]},{"name":"Kuhar","meanings":["Slovenian and Croatian: occupational name for a cook, from <i>kuhar</i>, a derivative of <i>kuhati</i> ‘to cook’. Compare   Cook  .","Americanized form of Slovak <b>Kuchár</b> ‘cook’ (see   Kuchar  ) and of its Ukrainian and Rusyn cognate <b>Kukhar</b>."]},{"name":"Cooke","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Cook  .","History: Francis Cooke (died 1663) and his eldest son John were passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1621; they were joined two years later by Francis's wife and other children. In the words of William Bradford, he lived long enough ‘to see his children's children have children’."]},{"name":"Kew","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>queu</i>, <i>keu</i>, <i>kieu</i>, <i>cu</i> ‘cook’, i.e. one who sold cooked meat, keeper of an eating house.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Caieu, a lost town in northern France, in the vicinity of Boulogne-sur-Mer.","Irish: shortened Ulster variant of   McHugh  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":28,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":53,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":66,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War o